TableContextTimeStampBeforeTable: {3070=David Cox (ALP) since 1998., 2308=Created in 1949 and named after Charles Kingston, the reforming Premier of South Australia and leader of the Federation movement in the state, as well as member of the first Federal Parliament and Ministry. Always a marginal seat, Kingston changed hands in 1966, 1969, 1975, 1983, 1996 and 1998. It was the seat contested by former Australian Democrats Leader Janine Haines in 1990. Held by former Labor Minister Gordon Bilney (1983-96), he was defeated in 1996, but after one term in the hands of Liberal Sue Jeanes, it reverted back to Labor in 1998. It was Labor's only gain in South Australia at an election where Labor needed to make many more gains in the state. For some reason, the electorate has the country's highest proportion people who answered 'none' to the religion question at the 2001 Census, 25.8% of the population., 1396=Labor majorities were recorded in 25 of the 27 booths from 2001. Assessment The closure of the Mitsubishi engine plant at Lonsdale within Kingston, and the fate of the Mitsubishi car assembly plant at Tonsley Park in neighbouring Boothby. Much of the workforce for these plants lives in Adelaide's southern suburbs. However, this is an issue more likely to work against the Howard government than against an opposition Labor MP. Issues and Polls The only South Australian seat re-gained by Labor since 1996, sitting MP Dave Cox a former senior adviser to Finance ministers in the Hawke government who spent the early 1990s growing grapes at Willunga before winning at the 1998 election. He is currently assistant Shadow Treasurer and Shadow spokesman on Revenue. The Liberal Party have a high profile candidate in Kym Richardson, who had a 27 year career in the S.A.
